1 Overview

For these exploratory runs there were 100 objectives to optimize, all with the target of 100 and an accuracy requirement of 99%. The population was size 512, and there was a point mutation probability of .7% at each objective. A solution is considered optimal if all of its traits meet the accuracy requirement.

4.1.1 Stats Tests

The Kuskal-Wallis test finds evidence that groups do not come from the same distribution.

kruskal.test(val ~ trt, data = df)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  val by trt
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 113.97, df = 4, p-value < 2.2e-16

We find evidence of no difference between 0,.1,.3,.6.

pairwise.wilcox.test(x = df$val, g = df$trt, p.adjust.method = "bonferroni", paired = FALSE, conf.int = TRUE, conf.level = .95, alternative = 't')
## 
##  Pairwise comparisons using Wilcoxon rank sum test 
## 
## data:  df$val and df$trt 
## 
##     0       0.1     0.3     0.6    
## 0.1 1.00    -       -       -      
## 0.3 1.00    1.00    -       -      
## 0.6 1.00    0.31    1.00    -      
## 1.2 1.1e-15 1.3e-15 4.9e-16 4.5e-15
## 
## P value adjustment method: bonferroni

5.1.2 Stats Tests

The Kuskal-Wallis test finds evidence that groups do not come from the same distribution.

kruskal.test(val ~ trt, data = df)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  val by trt
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 3.1042, df = 2, p-value = 0.2118

We find evidence that there is nostatistical difference between 15, 30, and 60. They have different values from all other groups (except 60).

pairwise.wilcox.test(x = df$val, g = df$trt, p.adjust.method = "bonferroni", paired = FALSE, conf.int = TRUE, conf.level = .95, alternative = 'l')
## 
##  Pairwise comparisons using Wilcoxon rank sum test 
## 
## data:  df$val and df$trt 
## 
##    15   30  
## 30 1.00 -   
## 60 0.12 0.12
## 
## P value adjustment method: bonferroni

6.1.1 Stats Tests

The Kuskal-Wallis test finds evidence that groups do not come from the same distribution.

kruskal.test(val ~ trt, data = df)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  val by trt
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 33.46, df = 4, p-value = 9.617e-07

We find evidence that 1.2, 2.5, and 5 have no statictical difference.

pairwise.wilcox.test(x = df$val, g = df$trt, p.adjust.method = "bonferroni", paired = FALSE, conf.int = TRUE, conf.level = .95, alternative = 't')
## 
##  Pairwise comparisons using Wilcoxon rank sum test 
## 
## data:  df$val and df$trt 
## 
##     0.6     1.2     2.5     5      
## 1.2 0.00271 -       -       -

## 5   1.7e-07 0.15339 0.63071 -      
## 10  0.01148 1.00000 1.00000 0.01647
## 
## P value adjustment method: bonferroni
pairwise.wilcox.test(x = df$val, g = df$trt, p.adjust.method = "bonferroni", paired = FALSE, conf.int = TRUE, conf.level = .95, alternative = 'g')
